{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655928"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:07:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18694"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18694"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.87,0.13,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76862"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11426"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10208"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26468"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76862"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBone formation requires specialised cells that produce and mineralise the extracellular matrix. This process is essential for skeletal development and bone repair throughout life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of osteoblasts in bone formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Generate new blood vessels","Produce and secrete osteoid matrix","Break down mineralised bone tissue","Transport calcium from blood to bone","Produce cartilage template"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of osteoblasts is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eproduce and secrete osteoid matrix\u003C/strong\u003E. Osteoblasts synthesise and secrete type I collagen and other proteins that form the organic bone matrix (osteoid). This matrix subsequently becomes mineralised through the deposition of hydroxyapatite crystals, forming mature bone tissue.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreak down mineralised bone tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of osteoclasts, not osteoblasts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport calcium from blood to bone\u003C/strong\u003E - While osteoblasts contribute to mineralisation, they do not directly transport calcium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerate new blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - This is performed by endothelial cells during angiogenesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduce cartilage template\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of chondrocytes during endochondral ossification\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs bone formation progresses, some osteoblasts become embedded within the mineralised matrix and differentiate into osteocytes, which form an interconnected network throughout the bone tissue.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteoblasts produce and secrete type I collagen and other proteins that form the organic bone matrix called osteoid.","Mineralisation of osteoid occurs through deposition of calcium and phosphate in the form of hydroxyapatite crystals.","Osteoblasts become trapped in mineralised bone matrix and transform into osteocytes, which maintain bone homeostasis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18694"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:35:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:36:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11426"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76862"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty